Livy wished to bring the facts of - their history, especially the facts of the noblest parts of it, as well as he could before the minds of his countrymen. ἓ 5. Cloacinae. The name, like cloaca, is derived from an old Latin word, cluerezpuryare. It is an epithet of Venus, derived, according to Pliny, from the purifying of the Romans with myrtle branches in the vicinity of her statue after the rape of the Sabines. But it is more probable that cloacina was an old Roman abstraction deity, afterwards iden- tified for some unknown reason with Venus.
